This principle states that objects of a superclass should be replaceable with objects of its subclasses without affecting the correctness of the program. In other words, if a class `B` is a subclass of class `A`, then any code that uses an object of type `A` should work seamlessly with an object of type `B`.

### Violation in the Code:

In the provided code, the `Ostrich` class extends the `Bird` class but overrides the `fly()` method to throw an `UnsupportedOperationException`. This violates LSP because it introduces a behavior that is not expected from a `Bird` (i.e., being able to fly). If you have a function or logic that assumes all `Bird` objects can fly, this assumption will be broken when dealing with an `Ostrich`.

### Example of Violation:

Consider the `simulateFlight()` method in the `FlightSimulator` class:
```kotlin
